text=!I want a bootable Gentoo USB Stick with Grub!%0a# Download the Gentoo ISO from the [[http://www.gentoo.org/main/en/mirrors.xml | Mirror-Site]]: http://bouncer.gentoo.org/fetch/gentoo-2008.0_beta2-livecd/x86/%0a# Put ext2 on the Stick with fdisk. Mark it bootable with "a".%0a# mkfs.ext2 /dev/sdb1 - You may have to load the ext2 Kernel Module.%0a# Unplug the stick, plug it back in. Make sure it shows up correctly in "dmesg".%0a# mount your Gentoo-ISO Image with "-o loop" to /mnt/cdrom.%0a# mount your USB stick to /mnt/usb.%0a# Copy the files from /mnt/cdrom/* to /mnt/usb with "cp -r".%0a# Run grub-install --root-directory=/mnt/usb /dev/sdb%0a# Make sure your BIOS settings are set to boot from USB.%0a# Reboot and Enjoy!%0a%0a!!Links%0a* http://mathias-kettner.de/lw_booten_von_usb.html%0a* http://www.gentoo.org/doc/en/liveusb.xml%0a%0a!How do I boot my customized Kernel from my USB-Grub-Stick?%0a# Copy your kernel bzImage from /usr/src/linux/arch/i386/boot/bzImage to your USB root.%0a# Boot from USB into Grub.%0a# Press c.%0a# Enter "kernel /bzImage".%0a# Enter "boot /bzImage" and your computer will boot from USB.%0a# Enjoy.%0a%0aNote: I find above useful in the case when you mess up your boot partition, say of your Server that is running a software raid. Above method is a lot faster then mounting and chrooting all over the place.
